<p><b>Democide</b> is a term coined by <a href="/wiki/Political_scientist" title="Political scientist" class="mw-redirect">political scientist</a> <a href="/wiki/R._J._Rummel" title="R. J. Rummel">R. J. Rummel</a> for "the <a href="/wiki/Murder" title="Murder">murder</a> of any person or people by a <a href="/wiki/Government" title="Government">government</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Genocide" title="Genocide">genocide</a>, <a href="/wiki/Politicide" title="Politicide">politicide</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Mass_murder" title="Mass murder">mass murder</a>." Rummel created the term as an extended concept to include forms of government murder that are not covered by the legal definition of <a href="/wiki/Genocide" title="Genocide">genocide</a>, and it has found currency among other scholars.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
<tr>
